children.subject: Took 127 this semester. I don't really remember using any concepts from math 53 that were super important. It is mostly a linear algebra based class, and the first month (which is review) goes very quickly and is pretty difficult imo. Other than "mathematical maturity," I don't think math 53 offers you much, but math 54 or equivalent is arguably essential. You really have to make sure you have a solid linalg background before 127.

Took Math 53 in CC then took EE 127 here. While it's definitely possible to do 127 without taking math 53 (provided you have a good enough linalg background from ee16ab/math54/math110), you are much better off having taken 53 since the course (at least when I took it) used the concepts of vector-valued functions, taking gradients, lagrange multipliers, etc. quite a bit. You can self-study the 53 material if you are motivated though, pm me and I can send some resources if you want

I took 127 without 53, and I think you will be fine if you have a solid understanding of calculus, as the multivariable concepts used in 127 are basically a generalization of the single variate examples you're likely familiar with. If you're interested in specific concepts, gradients show up a lot and the Hessian is important as well. Otherwise you should be good.

history.content: You're definitely fine taking 127 without 53 imo. I'd suggest learning what partial derivatives and gradients before taking 127, and maybe checking out basic vector and matrix calculus beyond that. Assuming you do all those things, you should be good to go!
Do you think it's essential to take math 53 before EE 127? Which topics would you recommend self-studying if math 53 isn't taken before 127?
